<br>
higher up conj really does own nowadays. But at lower level, hm...?<br>
Pets, focus items (some other bits) summoned prefight, you have time to med to get it back, however it IS a significant mana cost. And chaining pets if you go that road you really need conj specialization (while it maybe that max spec is a +17% bonus over all I still don't think it's a FIXED rate).<br>
<br>
Bumping up a skill isnt that hard, go to a newbie ground, nuke a mob and keep blasting it's corpse with lowest lvl spell of that type until oom, med, repeat, skills bump up quick. <br>
<br>
What spells do you plan on using at these levels? If you're gonna use a lot of fire evoc DD and Bolts, seriously think about Evoc. It takes a ruby, a significant expense at low lvl to change specializations by way.<br>
<br>
I notcied a horrific fizzle/resist rate on evoc spells (particularlly cinder bolt if I remember) until I had cast it a lot<br>
(yeah using a spell affects how it resists/fizzles! I always maxed my skills before going hunting, after dozens of casts with no level or skill changes you NOTICE resist/fizzle rates plunging back to normal from 80%+, and on same mobs as targets throughout) <br>
That point relaly showed up on Rains, manastorm had up to 100% resist rates on GREENS when I first had it, ugh!! few hours later was like 1 wave in three, no XP gained, no skills changed, same mobs same tactics but RESISTS CHANGED.<br>
<br>
Question is whether this happened due to the spells intrinsic nature, or to difference in Evoc/Conj specialization scores. I note all spells seem higher fizzle/resist rates at first but on conj it was very small.<br>
<br>
<br>
End of day pal, decide what spells you are going to use most in a day and specialize in it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
